Rating: 3
Ingredients, ingredients, ingredients. Curious isn't it, the drastic contrast in these love/hate responses? First of all, by no means are all sundride tomatoes created equal. Taste yours before you use them. It's absurd just how bad some can be. Also the quality of things labelled "gorgonzola" in this country, may have nothing in common with the traditional thing originally made in traditional ways, and first imported here, as there are not the strict guidelines inforced in Europe. Like that domesticly produced ham they call "prosciutto" and sell @ your local American supermarket: taste it side-by-side with the real thing produced in Parma or San Danelle and you'll see what I mean. And pinenuts can go rancid in a heart-beat, if stored improperly. With this kind of dish, as with most "Italian" cooking - it's all about the subtle qualities of the ingredients.

